    <bioghist>
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>The First Church of the Disciples of Christ in Philadelphia was chartered in 1841, though
        the church's membership roll dates back to 1835. By the twentieth century, the church was
        more commonly called the First Christian Church. The church was located at the intersection
        of Berks and Marvine Streets. The church was evidently struggling in 1912 when Irving S.
        Chenoweth became pastor. Chenoweth was born in 1883 and graduated from the Union Theological
        Seminary in 1911. Under Chenowith's leadership, the struggling church changed locations to
        one at the intersections of Tenth Street and Boulevard. First services at the new location
        were held on May 21, 1917. At some point after 1957, the church joined the United Church of
        Christ. It is unclear if the church continues to exist today in some form or fashion.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains membership and administrative records for the First Christian
        Church in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. The collection includes baptismal records, membership
        records, marriage records, records of deaths, church and board meeting minutes, newsletters,
        ladies aid society records, and an 1841 charter for the church.</p>
    </scopecontent>
